# Local CI Before Push

## The Rule

NEVER push code to a remote branch without first running the full CI pipeline
locally. GitHub Actions is not your test runner.

## Why This Exists

In the parent project, a session once spent 8+ CI round-trips debugging
failures that could have been caught locally in under 2 minutes. Each push
burned Actions minutes, added a multi-minute feedback delay, and wasted tokens
repeating the same fix-push-wait-read-fix cycle.

## Before Every Push — Run These Locally

```bash
./scripts/preflight.sh --mode pre-commit   # commit-time quick gate
./scripts/preflight.sh --mode pre-push     # push-time full gate
```

`scripts/preflight.sh` is the canonical wrapper used by local hooks, agent
sessions, and CI. All three surfaces run the same command — there is exactly
one definition of "passing."

## If Adding Dependencies

- Add Python deps to BOTH `requirements.txt` AND `pyproject.toml`, then verify
  a clean install (the canary test must still import everything).
- For Node deps, run the install, commit the lockfile, and re-run typecheck.

## If Changing Lint Config

Run the full lint pass locally BEFORE committing. Never promote a rule to
`error` if the codebase has unfixed violations — fix them in the same PR or
keep the rule at `warn`.

## Stop on Unexpected Tracked-File Mutation

If running tests or local CI mutates tracked files outside your feature area,
stop and inspect before committing. A passing test that dirties unrelated
tracked files is a hygiene problem, not "just noise."
